:QUOTE
A well-equipped cargo bike replaces most car trips for families within 10 km of daily destinations.

:INFO
Cargo Bike Setup for Everyday Errands
Configure a cargo bike as a practical car replacement for grocery runs, school pickup, and everyday errands. The right rack, bag, and weather gear system makes it usable year-round.

:COUNTER.half
$300
Typical accessories budget for a fully kitted cargo bike
|
:COUNTER.half
80%
Proportion of car trips replaceable by cargo bike in urban areas

:PATH
Add the Right Racks
A rear rack rated for 25 kg minimum handles most grocery loads. A front low-rider rack adds capacity for bulky items. Use racks with integrated bungee hooks for securing loads without panniers.

:PATH
Choose Bags and Containers
Ortlieb Back-Roller panniers are waterproof and durable. A large handlebar bag adds quick-access capacity. For kids, a Yepp or Thule child seat mounts to most rear racks rated 25 kg or more.

:PATH
Prepare for Weather
Fenders are mandatory. Add full-coverage SKS or Crud fenders if the bike did not come with them. Waterproof panniers handle rain automatically. Pogies or bar mitts keep hands warm in winter.

:CHECKLIST
Cargo Bike Setup Checklist
[ ] Confirm rear rack weight rating before buying accessories
[ ] Install front and rear racks with all bolts torqued to spec
[ ] Mount fenders if not already installed
[ ] Choose a pannier system and test fit before loading
[ ] Install front and rear lights rated for commuting brightness
[ ] Add a heavy-duty lock mounted to the frame
[ ] Test the fully loaded bike before your first errand run
[ ] Install child seat if needed and confirm weight limits

:NOTE
Distribute load evenly between front and rear to maintain steering feel. A heavily loaded rear rack with nothing up front makes a bike feel squirrelly at speed, especially on descents.
